  "output": "## Test coverage analysis — jobsquare\n\n**Zero tests exist.** No `tests/` dir, no `pytest.ini`/`pyproject.toml`, and `pytest` isn't even installed in `.venv` (only `httpx` + `PyYAML` are). Every function/class below is therefore \"untested\" — I've prioritized by risk (pure logic first, since it's cheap to test and most likely to silently regress; network/IO-bound fetchers next; CLI/process glue last).\n\nRecommended infra to add first: `pytest`, `pytest-asyncio`, `respx` (for mocking `httpx`), and a `tests/` package mirroring the modules.\n\n---\n\n### 1. `models.py` — highest value, zero dependencies\n\n**Untested:** `parse_posted_at`, `Job.key`, `Job.posted_dt`, `Job.content_hash`, `Job.to_row`.\n\n**Edge cases missed:**\n- `parse_posted_at`: empty string, `None`-ish falsy input, negative epoch, seconds-vs-milliseconds boundary (exactly `1_000_000_000_000`), garbage string, ISO string without `Z`/offset (naive → should coerce to UTC), ISO with `Z`.\n- `content_hash`: confirm it's stable across runs (no dict-ordering flakiness) and changes when title/location/url/department change but *not* when e.g. `posted_at` or `salary_range` change (that's the documented \"material change\" contract — currently only asserted by reading the code, never verified).\n- `to_row`: confirm `raw` is dropped and `key`/`content_hash` are injected.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_models.py\nimport pytest\nfrom datetime import timezone\nfrom models import Job, parse_posted_at\n\n@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"value,expected_none\", [\n    (\"\", True),\n    (None, True),\n    (\"not-a-date\", True),\n])\ndef test_parse_posted_at_unparseable_returns_none(value, expected_none):\n    assert (parse_posted_at(value) is None) == expected_none\n\ndef test_parse_posted_at_lever_milliseconds():\n    dt = parse_posted_at(\"1643241332430\")\n    assert dt.tzinfo is not None and dt.year == 2022\n\ndef test_parse_posted_at_seconds_vs_millis_boundary():\n    # exactly 1e12 must be treated as milliseconds, not seconds\n    dt = parse_posted_at(\"1000000000000\")\n    assert dt.year < 2100  # would be ~33658 if treated as seconds\n\ndef test_parse_posted_at_naive_iso_assumed_utc():\n    dt = parse_posted_at(\"2024-01-01T00:00:00\")\n    assert dt.tzinfo == timezone.utc\n\ndef test_parse_posted_at_z_suffix():\n    dt = parse_posted_at(\"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z\")\n    assert dt.utcoffset().total_seconds() == 0\n\ndef test_content_hash_changes_on_material_fields_only():\n    j1 = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\", url=\"u\", location=\"NYC\")\n    j2 = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\", url=\"u\", location=\"NYC\",\n              salary_range=\"$999k\")  # non-material field\n    assert j1.content_hash == j2.content_hash\n    j3 = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng II\", url=\"u\", location=\"NYC\")\n    assert j1.content_hash != j3.content_hash\n\ndef test_key_is_stable_identity():\n    j = Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"42\", title=\"x\", url=\"u\")\n    assert j.key == \"greenhouse:acme:42\"\n\ndef test_to_row_drops_raw_and_adds_derived_fields():\n    j = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"t\", url=\"u\", raw={\"x\": 1})\n    row = j.to_row()\n    assert \"raw\" not in row\n    assert row[\"key\"] == j.key and row[\"content_hash\"] == j.content_hash\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `filters.py`\n\n**Untested:** `match`, `filter_jobs`, `_compile`.\n\n**Edge cases missed:**\n- Word-boundary regex behavior: `include=[\"go\"]` shouldn't match \"Django\" (tests the `\\b` boundary is doing its job) but should match \"Go Engineer\".\n- Empty/`None` include/exclude/locations lists (falsy — should be a no-op, not raise).\n- Location matching is substring + case-insensitive — verify \"sf\" doesn't accidentally match unless it's a real substring, and that `\"New York\"` matches `locations=[\"new york\"]`.\n- Exclude takes precedence over include when both match.\n- `cutoff` with an unparseable `posted_at` — job must be **kept** (documented behavior), not dropped.\n- `max_age_days` as a float/string from YAML (e.g. `\"3.5\"`).\n\n```python\n# tests/test_filters.py\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone\nfrom models import Job\nfrom filters import match, filter_jobs\n\ndef _job(title=\"Software Engineer\", location=\"Remote\", department=\"\", posted_at=\"\"):\n    return Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=title, url=\"u\",\n               location=location, department=department, posted_at=posted_at)\n\ndef test_include_respects_word_boundary():\n    assert not match(_job(title=\"Django Developer\"), include=[\"go\"])\n    assert match(_job(title=\"Go Developer\"), include=[\"go\"])\n\ndef test_exclude_wins_over_include():\n    j = _job(title=\"Senior Staff Engineer (Intern mentor)\")\n    assert not match(j, include=[\"engineer\"], exclude=[\"intern\"])\n\ndef test_empty_filters_are_noop():\n    j = _job()\n    assert match(j, include=[], exclude=[], locations=[])\n    assert match(j, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None)\n\ndef test_location_substring_case_insensitive():\n    assert match(_job(location=\"New York, NY\"), locations=[\"new york\"])\n    assert not match(_job(location=\"Austin, TX\"), locations=[\"new york\"])\n\ndef test_cutoff_keeps_unparseable_posted_at():\n    old_cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) + timedelta(days=1)  # cutoff in the future\n    assert match(_job(posted_at=\"garbage\"), cutoff=old_cutoff)\n\ndef test_cutoff_drops_stale_job():\n    cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc)\n    stale = _job(posted_at=(cutoff - timedelta(days=10)).isoformat())\n    assert not match(stale, cutoff=cutoff)\n\ndef test_filter_jobs_max_age_days_from_yaml_string():\n    fresh = _job(posted_at=datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat())\n    stale = _job(posted_at=(datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=30)).isoformat())\n    out = filter_jobs([fresh, stale], {\"max_age_days\": \"7\"})\n    assert out == [fresh]\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `store.py` — needs a `tmp_path` SQLite fixture\n\n**Untested:** `Store.__init__`/`_migrate`, `diff` (new/changed/unchanged branches), `get_meta`/`set_meta` (insert + upsert), `added_since`, `count`, context-manager protocol.\n\n**Edge cases missed:**\n- `_migrate` against a *pre-existing* DB file created before `salary_range` existed (simulate by creating the table without that column, then opening with `Store`).\n- `diff` called twice with the same jobs → second call should report 0 new / 0 changed but still bump `last_seen`.\n- `diff` with a job whose non-material field changed (e.g. `posted_at`) but `content_hash` unchanged → should **not** appear in `changed`.\n- `added_since` ordering (oldest first, tie-broken by company/title) and the strict `>` boundary (a row with `first_seen == ts` must be excluded).\n- `set_meta` upsert path (calling twice with different values keeps only the latest).\n- Empty `jobs` list to `diff`.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_store.py\nimport sqlite3\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Job\nfrom store import Store\n\ndef _job(ext_id, title=\"Eng\", **kw):\n    return Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"acme\", external_id=ext_id, title=title, url=\"u\", **kw)\n\n@pytest.fixture\ndef store(tmp_path):\n    with Store(tmp_path / \"jobs.db\") as s:\n        yield s\n\ndef test_diff_new_then_unchanged_then_changed(store):\n    j = _job(\"1\")\n    new, changed = store.diff([j])\n    assert new == [j] and changed == []\n\n    new, changed = store.diff([j])  # identical -> neither bucket\n    assert new == [] and changed == []\n\n    j2 = _job(\"1\", title=\"Eng II\")  # material change\n    new, changed = store.diff([j2])\n    assert new == [] and changed == [j2]\n\ndef test_diff_ignores_non_material_change(store):\n    store.diff([_job(\"1\", posted_at=\"2024-01-01T00:00:00Z\")])\n    _, changed = store.diff([_job(\"1\", posted_at=\"2024-06-01T00:00:00Z\")])\n    assert changed == []  # posted_at isn't part of content_hash\n\ndef test_migrate_adds_salary_range_to_legacy_db(tmp_path):\n    path = tmp_path / \"legacy.db\"\n    conn = sqlite3.connect(path)\n    conn.execute(\"\"\"CREATE TABLE jobs (key TEXT PRIMARY KEY, source TEXT, company TEXT,\n        external_id TEXT, title TEXT, url TEXT, location TEXT, department TEXT,\n        employment_type TEXT, posted_at TEXT, content_hash TEXT,\n        first_seen TEXT, last_seen TEXT)\"\"\")\n    conn.commit(); conn.close()\n\n    with Store(path) as s:\n        cols = {r[\"name\"] for r in s.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA table_info(jobs)\")}\n        assert \"salary_range\" in cols\n\ndef test_added_since_excludes_exact_boundary_and_orders(store):\n    store.diff([_job(\"1\")])\n    ts = store.conn.execute(\"SELECT first_seen FROM jobs\").fetchone()[0]\n    assert store.added_since(ts) == []  # strict > only\n    assert len(store.added_since(\"1970-01-01T00:00:00+00:00\")) == 1\n\ndef test_set_meta_upserts(store):\n    store.set_meta(\"last_scan\", \"a\")\n    store.set_meta(\"last_scan\", \"b\")\n    assert store.get_meta(\"last_scan\") == \"b\"\n\ndef test_get_meta_missing_key_returns_none(store):\n    assert store.get_meta(\"nope\") is None\n\ndef test_diff_empty_list(store):\n    assert store.diff([]) == ([], [])\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `fetchers.py` — largest surface, mostly untested\n\n#### 4a. Parsers (pure functions — cheap, high value)\n\nUntested: `parse_greenhouse`, `parse_lever`, `_lever_salary`, `parse_ashby`, `_ashby_salary`, `parse_smartrecruiters`, `parse_recruitee`, `parse_workable`, `_extract_ds1`, `_ds1_posted_at`, `parse_google`, `parse_deshaw`, `parse_twosigma`, `parse_optiver`, `parse_meta`, `parse_microsoft`, `parse_netflix`, `_amazon_posted_at`, `parse_amazon`.\n\n**Edge cases missed per parser** (these are the kind of thing that breaks silently when an ATS tweaks its payload):\n- `parse_lever`/`_lever_salary`: missing `salaryRange`, only one of `min`/`max` set, non-numeric salary values, missing `categories` key entirely.\n- `parse_ashby`: `isListed: False` must be filtered out; missing `id` falls back to `jobId`.\n- `parse_workable`: location as dict vs. flat string (two branches).\n- `parse_recruitee`: location built from `city`/`country` when `location` key absent.\n- `_extract_ds1`: HTML with no `ds:1` blob at all (should return `[]`, not raise); malformed JSON in the blob (`json.JSONDecodeError` swallowed); the fallback regex path when `sideChannel` is missing.\n- `parse_google`: job entry that's falsy/`None`/empty (`if not j or not j[0]: continue`); short arrays (index-out-of-range guards at `j[1]`, `j[7]`, `j[9]`).\n- `_ds1_posted_at`: no timestamp at any of indices 12/13/14 → `\"\"`; array shorter than 13 elements.\n- `parse_deshaw`: duplicate `data-job-id` in the page (the `seen` set); card missing a title (`mid and mtitle` guard) — should be skipped, not raise; HTML-entity unescaping in title/location.\n- `parse_twosigma`: same job rendered 3× (dedup via `seen`); last anchor in the page (the `i+1 < len(anchors)` boundary for slicing `end`).\n- `parse_optiver`: `href` without the `join-us/jobs/` prefix falls back to raw href as `external_id`.\n- `parse_meta`: duplicate/missing `id`, `locations`/`teams` as `None` (not just missing key — `.get(...) or []` guards).\n- `_amazon_posted_at`: malformed date string → `\"\"` (currently only tested by inspection); single-digit day.\n- `parse_microsoft`/`parse_netflix`: missing `postedTs`/`t_create` → `posted_at=\"\"`; Netflix's `location` singular fallback when `locations` list absent; comma-packed location splitting.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_parsers.py\nfrom fetchers import (parse_lever, _lever_salary, parse_ashby, parse_workable,\n                       _extract_ds1, parse_google, _ds1_posted_at, parse_deshaw,\n                       parse_meta, _amazon_posted_at, parse_amazon, parse_netflix)\n\ndef test_lever_salary_missing_range_falls_back_to_plain_text():\n    assert _lever_salary({\"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"Competitive\"}) == \"Competitive\"\n    assert _lever_salary({}) == \"\"\n\ndef test_lever_salary_partial_range_ignored():\n    assert _lever_salary({\"salaryRange\": {\"min\": 100}, \"salaryDescriptionPlain\": \"DOE\"}) == \"DOE\"\n\ndef test_parse_ashby_filters_unlisted_and_falls_back_to_job_id():\n    data = {\"jobs\": [{\"isListed\": False, \"id\": \"1\", \"title\": \"hidden\"},\n                     {\"jobId\": \"2\", \"title\": \"shown\"}]}\n    out = parse_ashby(\"acme\", data)\n    assert [j.external_id for j in out] == [\"2\"]\n\ndef test_parse_workable_location_dict_vs_string():\n    dict_loc = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": \"1\", \"location\": {\"location_str\": \"Remote\"}}]}\n    flat_loc = {\"jobs\": [{\"id\": \"2\", \"city\": \"Austin\", \"country\": \"US\"}]}\n    assert parse_workable(\"c\", dict_loc)[0].location == \"Remote\"\n    assert parse_workable(\"c\", flat_loc)[0].location == \"Austin, US\"\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_no_blob_returns_empty():\n    assert _extract_ds1(\"<html>nothing here</html>\") == []\n\ndef test_extract_ds1_malformed_json_returns_empty():\n    html = \"key: 'ds:1', data:[not valid json,,, ], sideChannel\"\n    assert _extract_ds1(html) == []\n\ndef test_parse_google_skips_falsy_entries_and_short_arrays():\n    assert parse_google(\"google\", [None, [], [\"123\"]]) == []  # no j[0] truthy w/ len>1... covers guards\n    out = parse_google(\"google\", [[\"123\", \"Title\"]])\n    assert out[0].title == \"Title\" and out[0].location == \"\"\n\ndef test_ds1_posted_at_missing_timestamps():\n    assert _ds1_posted_at([\"id\", \"title\"]) == \"\"\n\ndef test_parse_deshaw_dedupes_and_skips_incomplete_cards():\n    page = ('<div data-job-id=\"1\" class=\"job-display-name\">Eng</div>'\n            '<div data-job-id=\"1\" class=\"job-display-name\">Eng dup</div>'\n            '<div data-job-id=\"2\"></div>')  # no title -> skipped\n    out = parse_deshaw(\"deshaw\", page)\n    assert [j.external_id for j in out] == [\"1\"]\n\ndef test_parse_meta_dedupes_and_handles_missing_id():\n    results = [{\"id\": \"1\", \"title\": \"A\"}, {\"id\": \"1\", \"title\": \"dup\"}, {\"title\": \"no id\"}]\n    out = parse_meta(\"meta\", results)\n    assert [j.external_id for j in out] == [\"1\"]\n\ndef test_amazon_posted_at_malformed_returns_empty():\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"not a date\") == \"\"\n    assert _amazon_posted_at(\"June 26, 2026\") == \"2026-06-26T00:00:00+00:00\"\n\ndef test_parse_amazon_id_icims_fallback():\n    out = parse_amazon(\"amazon\", [{\"id_icims\": \"abc\", \"title\": \" Eng \"}])\n    assert out[0].external_id == \"abc\" and out[0].title == \"Eng\"\n\ndef test_parse_netflix_singular_location_fallback():\n    out = parse_netflix(\"netflix\", [{\"id\": \"1\", \"location\": \"SF,CA,US\", \"t_create\": 1700000000}])\n    assert out[0].location == \"SF, CA, US\"\n```\n\n#### 4b. `_request` retry/backoff logic — currently completely unverified\n\nThis is the riskiest untested code in the repo: retry-on-`429/500/502/503/504`, exponential backoff, exhaustion → `RuntimeError`, and non-retryable errors (e.g. 404) should **not** retry.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_request.py\nimport httpx\nimport pytest\nfrom fetchers import _request\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_retries_on_503_then_succeeds(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"fetchers.asyncio.sleep\", lambda *_: None)  # skip real backoff\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(request):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        if calls[\"n\"] < 3:\n            return httpx.Response(503)\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"ok\": True})\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        r = await _request(client, \"https://x.test/\")\n    assert r.status_code == 200 and calls[\"n\"] == 3\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_exhausts_retries_raises_runtime_error(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"fetchers.asyncio.sleep\", lambda *_: None)\n    async def handler(request):\n        return httpx.Response(500)\n    transport = httpx.MockTransport(lambda r: httpx.Response(500))\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=transport) as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x.test/\", retries=2)\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_request_does_not_retry_non_retryable_4xx():\n    calls = {\"n\": 0}\n    def handler(request):\n        calls[\"n\"] += 1\n        return httpx.Response(404)\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler)) as client:\n        with pytest.raises(RuntimeError):\n            await _request(client, \"https://x.test/\")\n    assert calls[\"n\"] == 1\n```\n\n#### 4c. Pagination loops (`fetch_workday`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_meta`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_twosigma`, `fetch_optiver`)\n\n**Untested for every one of these:** stop-on-empty-page condition, dedup-by-`external_id` across pages, `max_pages` safety cap actually being honored, and (for `fetch_workday`) the `offset >= total` and `offset > 5000` cap.\n\n**Special case — `fetch_meta`:** the `\"for (;;);\"` JSON-hijacking prefix strip, and the `data.get(\"errors\")` → `RuntimeError` path when the persisted-query `doc_id` rotates (this is explicitly called out as a known failure mode in the module docstring but has no regression test).\n\n```python\n# tests/test_fetchers_pagination.py\nimport json\nimport httpx\nimport pytest\nfrom fetchers import fetch_workday, fetch_meta\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_workday_stops_when_offset_reaches_total():\n    def handler(request):\n        body = json.loads(request.content)\n        offset = body[\"offset\"]\n        if offset == 0:\n            return httpx.Response(200, json={\"total\": 1, \"jobPostings\": [\n                {\"externalPath\": \"/job/1\", \"bulletFields\": [\"R1\"], \"title\": \"Eng\"}]})\n        return httpx.Response(200, json={\"total\": 1, \"jobPostings\": []})\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler))\n    jobs = await fetch_workday(client, {\"host\": \"h\", \"tenant\": \"t\", \"site\": \"s\"})\n    await client.aclose()\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_meta_raises_on_graphql_error_rotated_doc_id():\n    def handler(request):\n        if request.url.path.endswith(\"/jobs\"):\n            return httpx.Response(200, text='<script>[\"LSD\",[],{\"token\":\"t\"}]</script>')\n        return httpx.Response(200, text=json.dumps({\"errors\": [{\"message\": \"bad doc_id\"}]}))\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler))\n    with pytest.raises(RuntimeError, match=\"bad doc_id\"):\n        await fetch_meta(client, {})\n    await client.aclose()\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_meta_strips_for_loop_prefix():\n    def handler(request):\n        if request.url.path.endswith(\"/jobs\"):\n            return httpx.Response(200, text=\"\")\n        payload = {\"data\": {\"job_search_with_featured_jobs_v2\": {\"all_jobs\": []}}}\n        return httpx.Response(200, text=\"for (;;);\" + json.dumps(payload))\n    client = httpx.AsyncClient(transport=httpx.MockTransport(handler))\n    jobs = await fetch_meta(client, {})\n    await client.aclose()\n    assert jobs == []\n```\n\n#### 4d. `fetch_source` / `fetch_all` (integration within the module)\n\n- `fetch_source` with an unknown `ats` → `ValueError` listing known ATSes (untested).\n- `fetch_all`: one source raising should **not** kill the others (`except Exception` swallow + `[]` fallback) — this is the module's core resilience guarantee and has zero regression coverage. Also verify `concurrency` actually caps in-flight requests, and that results flatten in a stable way.\n\n```python\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_source_unknown_ats_raises_value_error():\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"unknown ATS\"):\n        await fetch_source(None, {\"ats\": \"bogus\"})\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_fetch_all_isolates_failing_source(monkeypatch, capsys):\n    async def ok(client, source): return [Job(source=\"greenhouse\", company=\"ok\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"t\", url=\"u\")]\n    async def boom(client, source): raise RuntimeError(\"network down\")\n    monkeypatch.setitem(fetchers.FETCHERS, \"greenhouse\", ok)\n    monkeypatch.setitem(fetchers.FETCHERS, \"lever\", boom)\n    jobs = await fetch_all([{\"ats\": \"greenhouse\", \"company\": \"ok\"},\n                            {\"ats\": \"lever\", \"company\": \"bad\"}])\n    assert len(jobs) == 1\n    assert \"failed\" in capsys.readouterr().out\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `notify.py`\n\n**Untested:** `_line`, `notify_console`, `notify_slack`, `notify_webhook`, `notify_email`, `_sms_body`, `notify_sms`, `dispatch`.\n\n**Edge cases / error-handling gaps (this is where the real risk is):**\n- Every `notify_*` besides console short-circuits when its env var is unset — none of those guard clauses are tested.\n- Every `notify_*` short-circuits when `new`/`changed` are both empty **even if configured** — untested.\n- `notify_sms`/`_sms_body`: the `limit` truncation and `\"+N more\"` line; ASCII-only comment implies GSM-7 concerns but nothing asserts no non-ASCII chars leak in; `resp.raise_for_status()` propagating on bad Twilio creds.\n- `notify_email`: optional `SMTP_USER`/`SMTP_PASS` login branch vs. anonymous SMTP.\n- **`dispatch`'s exception isolation is the most important untested behavior in this file** — one notifier raising must not block the others, and must print a `! notifier {name} failed: {e}` line.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_notify.py\nimport httpx\nimport pytest\nfrom models import Job\nimport notify\n\ndef _job(title=\"Eng\"):\n    return Job(source=\"s\", company=\"acme\", external_id=\"1\", title=title, url=\"http://x\")\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_without_webhook_url(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.delenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", raising=False)\n    calls = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(httpx, \"post\", lambda *a, **k: calls.append(1))\n    notify.notify_slack([_job()], [])\n    assert calls == []\n\ndef test_notify_slack_noop_when_nothing_to_report(monkeypatch):\n    monkeypatch.setenv(\"SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL\", \"http://hook\")\n    calls = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(httpx, \"post\", lambda *a, **k: calls.append(1))\n    notify.notify_slack([], [])\n    assert calls == []\n\ndef test_notify_sms_truncates_and_counts_remainder():\n    jobs = [_job(f\"Role {i}\") for i in range(10)]\n    body = notify._sms_body(jobs, [], limit=8)\n    assert \"+2 more\" in body\n    assert body.count(\"- Role\") == 8\n\ndef test_notify_sms_missing_env_var_noop(monkeypatch):\n    for k in (\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\", \"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\", \"TWILIO_FROM\", \"TWILIO_TO\"):\n        monkeypatch.delenv(k, raising=False)\n    calls = []\n    monkeypatch.setattr(httpx, \"post\", lambda *a, **k: calls.append(1))\n    notify.notify_sms([_job()], [])\n    assert calls == []\n\ndef test_notify_sms_raises_on_bad_credentials(monkeypatch):\n    for k, v in {\"TWILIO_ACCOUNT_SID\": \"s\", \"TWILIO_AUTH_TOKEN\": \"t\",\n                 \"TWILIO_FROM\": \"+1\", \"TWILIO_TO\": \"+2\"}.items():\n        monkeypatch.setenv(k, v)\n    def fake_post(*a, **k):\n        return httpx.Response(401, request=httpx.Request(\"POST\", \"http://x\"))\n    monkeypatch.setattr(httpx, \"post\", fake_post)\n    with pytest.raises(httpx.HTTPStatusError):\n        notify.notify_sms([_job()], [])\n\ndef test_dispatch_isolates_failing_notifier(monkeypatch, capsys):\n    def boom(new, changed): raise RuntimeError(\"smtp down\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(notify, \"NOTIFIERS\", [notify.notify_console, boom])\n    notify.dispatch([_job()], [])\n    out = capsys.readouterr().out\n    assert \"notifier boom failed\" in out\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. `pipeline.py` / `cli.py` — integration gaps\n\n**Untested:** `load_config` (defaults for missing `sources`/`filters`/`db`/`concurrency`), `run` (fetch → filter → dry-run branch vs. persisted branch), `run_sync`, `cli.main` argument parsing (`--config`, `--dry-run`).\n\nThis is the actual integration point tying fetchers → filters → store → notify together, and it has **no end-to-end test at all**.\n\n```python\n# tests/test_pipeline.py\nimport pytest\nfrom pipeline import load_config, run\n\ndef test_load_config_defaults(tmp_path):\n    cfg_file = tmp_path / \"cfg.yaml\"\n    cfg_file.write_text(\"sources: []\\n\")\n    cfg = load_config(cfg_file)\n    assert cfg[\"filters\"] == {} and cfg[\"db\"] == \"jobs.db\" and cfg[\"concurrency\"] == 8\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_run_dry_run_does_not_touch_store(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    cfg_file = tmp_path / \"cfg.yaml\"\n    cfg_file.write_text(f\"sources: []\\ndb: {tmp_path / 'jobs.db'}\\n\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", lambda *a, **k: [])\n    result = await run(cfg_file, dry_run=True)\n    assert result == {\"matched\": 0, \"new\": 0, \"changed\": 0}\n    assert not (tmp_path / \"jobs.db\").exists()\n\n@pytest.mark.asyncio\nasync def test_run_persists_and_dispatches(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    from models import Job\n    j = Job(source=\"s\", company=\"c\", external_id=\"1\", title=\"Eng\", url=\"u\")\n    cfg_file = tmp_path / \"cfg.yaml\"\n    cfg_file.write_text(f\"sources: []\\ndb: {tmp_path / 'jobs.db'}\\n\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"pipeline.fetch_all\", lambda *a, **k: [j])\n    dispatched = {}\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"pipeline.dispatch\", lambda new, changed: dispatched.update(new=new))\n    result = await run(cfg_file, dry_run=False)\n    assert result[\"new\"] == 1 and dispatched[\"new\"] == [j]\n```\n\n```python\n# tests/test_cli.py\nfrom cli import main\n\ndef test_cli_dry_run_flag(monkeypatch):\n    captured = {}\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"cli.run_sync\", lambda cfg, dry_run: captured.update(cfg=cfg, dry_run=dry_run))\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"sys.argv\", [\"cli.py\", \"-c\", \"custom.yaml\", \"--dry-run\"])\n    main()\n    assert captured == {\"cfg\": \"custom.yaml\", \"dry_run\": True}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 7. `agent.py`\n\n**Untested:** `cmd_db_new` (first-run window vs. marker-based, `--limit` truncation at group boundaries, `groupby` batching logic), `cmd_db_mark` (`--now` vs explicit watermark vs. invalid ISO string vs. neither given), `_normalize_ats` (all 14 replacement rules, and the \"skip inside tags/style/script\" invariant), `_chrome_bin` (env override, `PATH` lookup, hardcoded app paths, none-found → `sys.exit`), `cmd_pdf_render` (missing input file, successful render, failed render — non-`%PDF` output), `run_claude`/`main`'s argv parsing (bare invocation → interactive, mode words vs. flags split).\n\n**Highest-value gaps:**\n- `_normalize_ats` correctness inside `<style>`/`<script>` tags — the whole point of that function is *not* mangling markup, and it's currently unverified.\n- `cmd_db_new`'s truncation-at-group-boundary logic (`if jobs and len(jobs) + len(g) > a.limit: truncated = True; break`) — subtle off-by-one-prone code, no test.\n- `cmd_db_mark` rejecting a malformed watermark (`return 2`).\n\n```python\n# tests/test_agent.py\nimport pytest\nfrom agent import _normalize_ats, cmd_db_mark, cmd_db_new\nfrom store import Store\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_skips_style_and_script_blocks():\n    html = \"<style>content: '\\u2014';</style><p>em\\u2014dash</p><script>var x='\\u2014';</script>\"\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    assert \"content: '\\u2014'\" in out          # untouched inside <style>\n    assert \"var x='\\u2014'\" in out              # untouched inside <script>\n    assert \"em-dash\" in out                    # replaced in body text\n    assert counts[\"em-dash\"] == 1\n\ndef test_normalize_ats_all_rules_fire():\n    html = \"\\u2018q\\u2019 \\u201Cd\\u201D \\u2026 \\u00A0 \\u2192 \\u2190 \\u2191 \\u00B7 \\u2022 \\u20AC \\u00A3\"\n    out, counts = _normalize_ats(html)\n    for label in (\"smart-single-quote\", \"smart-double-quote\", \"ellipsis\", \"nbsp\",\n                  \"right-arrow\", \"left-arrow\", \"vert-arrow\", \"middot\", \"bullet\",\n                  \"euro\", \"pound\"):\n        assert counts.get(label, 0) >= 1\n\ndef test_db_mark_rejects_invalid_watermark(tmp_path, capsys):\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([\"not-a-date\", \"-c\", str(tmp_path / \"missing.yaml\")])\n    assert rc == 2\n\ndef test_db_mark_requires_watermark_or_now(tmp_path, capsys):\n    rc = cmd_db_mark([])\n    assert rc == 2\n\ndef test_db_new_truncates_at_group_boundary(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    # seed store with two first_seen groups, sizes 3 and 3; limit=4 should\n    # keep only the first group of 3, not split the second group's tail\n    ...  # build via Store.diff() with monkeypatched timestamps, then assert\n         # result[\"truncated\"] is True and result[\"count\"] == 3\n```\n\n---\n\n### Priority ranking for actually writing these\n\n1. **`models.py`, `filters.py`** — pure, deterministic, no fixtures needed. Do these first.\n2. **Parsers in `fetchers.py`** (4a) — pure, and this is the code most likely to break silently when an ATS changes its payload shape (already happened once per Meta's doc_id comment).\n3. **`store.py`** — needs only `tmp_path`, cheap to set up, protects the dedup contract everything else relies on.\n4. **`notify.py` `dispatch` isolation + env-var guards** — protects against one bad notifier config breaking all notifications.\n5. **`_request` retry logic + pagination loops** (4b/4c) — needs `respx`/`MockTransport`, higher setup cost but covers the riskiest network code.\n6. **`pipeline.py`/`cli.py` integration** and **`agent.py`** — lowest risk of silent regression (mostly glue), do last.\n\nWant me to scaffold `tests/` with `conftest.py`, add `pytest`/`pytest-asyncio`/`respx` to `requirements.txt` (or a new `requirements-dev.txt`), and implement the models/filters/store suites first?\n",
